issue.body: ## Communicate using Markdown ðŸ‘‹ Hey there @24127031-Jishnu! Welcome to your Skills exercise! Organize ideas and collaborate using Markdown, a lightweight language for text formatting. --- âœ¨ **This is an interactive, hands-on GitHub Skills exercise!** As you complete each step, Iâ€™ll leave updates in the comments: - âœ… Check your work and guide you forward - ðŸ’¡ Share helpful tips and resources - ðŸš€ Celebrate your progress and completion Letâ€™s get started - good luck and have fun! â€” Mona

comment.body:
## Step 1: Add headings **What is _Markdown_?** Markdown is a [lightweight syntax](https://docs.github.com/github/writing-on-github/getting-started-with-writing-and-formatting-on-github/basic-writing-and-formatting-syntax) for communicating on GitHub. You can format text to add a heading, lists, **bold**, _italics_, tables, and many other stylings. You can use Markdown in most places around GitHub such as: - Comments on [issues](https://docs.github.com/issues/tracking-your-work-with-issues/about-issues), [pull requests](https://docs.github.com/pull-requests/collaborating-with-pull-requests/proposing-changes-to-your-work-with-pull-requests/about-pull-requests), and [discussions](https://docs.github.com/discussions/collaborating-with-your-community-using-discussions/about-discussions) - Files with the `.md` or `.markdown` extension - Snippets of text in [Gists](https://docs.github.com/github/writing-on-github/editing-and-sharing-content-with-gists/creating-gists) **What is a _heading_?** A heading is a larger bit of text at the beginning of a section. There are six sizes. ### Example ```md # This is an `

` heading, which is the largest ## This is an `

` heading ###### This is an `

`heading, which is the smallest ``` # This is an `

` heading, which is the largest ## This is an `

` heading ###### This is an `

` heading, which is the smallest ### âŒ¨ï¸ Activity: Create a markdown file 1. Open a new browser tab, and work on the steps in your second tab while you read the instructions in this tab. 1. In the top navigation, select the **Code** tab. 1. Create a new branch with the following name: ```md start-blog ``` 1. Above the files list, click the **Add file** button and select **Create new file**. 1. Use the following file name. ```md day-1.md ``` 1. In the editor, on the first line use a level one heading to give the page a title. ```md # Daily Learning ``` 1. Add a couple level 2 headings for the names of each of the blog posts. ```md ## Morning Planning ## Review ``` 1. Above the editor, click the **Preview** toggle to view the rendered version. 1. In the top right, click the **Commit changes** button and commit directly to the `start-blog` branch. 1. With our headings created and committed, Mona should be busy reviewing your work and preparing the next steps.
Having trouble? ðŸ¤·
- Confirm you are editing the correct file and branch. - Double check your syntax. The must be a space between the `#` and first word.

pull_request.title: Initialize repository
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces Prettier code formatting to the project, adds configuration for automated formatting checks in CI, and includes a new user style for the `tver.jp` website. The most important changes are grouped below:

**Prettier Integration and Automation:**

* Added a Prettier configuration file `.prettierrc` to define code formatting rules for the project.
* Created a `.prettierignore` file to specify files and directories that should be excluded from formatting.
* Updated `package.json` to include Prettier as a dev dependency and added scripts for formatting and checking code style.
* Added a GitHub Actions workflow `.github/workflows/prettier.yml` to automatically run Prettier checks on pull requests targeting the `main` branch.

**New User Style:**

* Added `css/tver.user.css`, a user style for the `tver.jp` website, which increases the maximum width of certain layout containers for a better viewing experience.

Issue #31: Complete Authentication & Authorization System

- Comprehensive authentication infrastructure with user management, session handling, and password security
- Role-based access control (RBAC) with hierarchical permissions and access control lists (ACLs)
- Multi-factor authentication (MFA) with TOTP support, backup codes, and QR code generation
- Advanced security features: account lockout, password policies, audit logging, session management
- Complete integration with kernel security hooks for file system, process management, and network access
- Comprehensive test suite covering all authentication, authorization, and MFA functionality
- Enterprise-grade security suitable for production systems with industry-standard cryptography

Components:
- auth_system.h: Complete API definitions and data structures (600+ lines)
- auth_core.c: Core authentication engine with user management and session handling
- auth_authorization.c: Role-based access control and permission management
- auth_mfa.c: Multi-factor authentication with TOTP and backup codes
- auth_test.c: Comprehensive test suite with security validation
- AUTHENTICATION_INTEGRATION.md: Integration guide with kernel security hooks

Security Features:
- bcrypt/PBKDF2 password hashing with salt
- Cryptographically secure session tokens
- TOTP-based multi-factor authentication
- Account lockout protection against brute force
- Comprehensive audit logging and event tracking
- Fine-grained access control with ACLs
- Role hierarchy with permission inheritance
